# No Direct Commits to Main

**Never** create commits on `main` or `master`. All changes must go through a feature branch and be merged via PR.

## Before Every Commit

Run `git branch --show-current`. If the result is `main` or `master`, **STOP** — do not commit.

1. Stash or stage the changes
2. Create a feature branch following the naming convention
3. Only then commit on the new branch

## Forbidden Operations on Main

- `git commit` (any form)
- `git merge` (local merges into main)
- `git cherry-pick`
- `git revert` (create a revert branch instead)

## If You Catch Yourself on Main

```bash
# Stash work, create branch, re-apply
git stash
git checkout -b feat/<DUO-XX>/<description>
git stash pop
```

## No Exceptions

Even "quick fixes" or "one-line changes" must go through a branch. There are no changes small enough to justify committing directly to main.
